# Ways of Working: {{ display_name }}

## Definition of Done

A feature or bug fix is considered done when ALL of the following are true:

- [ ] Code is written and passes all lint and format checks
- [ ] Tests are written, passing, and match the **{{ test_strategy }}** strategy
- [ ] New or changed endpoints are reflected in the OpenAPI spec{% if use_openapi %} (auto-generated or manually updated){% endif %}
- [ ] Error cases are handled and return correct HTTP status codes and error envelopes
- [ ] Documentation is updated if the change affects architecture, API design, or data models
- [ ] Code has been reviewed by at least one team member
- [ ] The change has been tested against a real {{ database }} instance (locally or in CI)
{% if use_auth %}
- [ ] Authorization rules are in place: authenticated routes require a valid token; resource access is scoped to the requesting user or role
{% endif %}
- [ ] No secrets or environment-specific values are committed to source control

## Branching Strategy

We use trunk-based development with short-lived feature branches.

### Branch Naming

```
feature/<ticket-id>-<short-description>
fix/<ticket-id>-<short-description>
chore/<description>
docs/<description>
api/<ticket-id>-<resource-or-endpoint>
```

### Workflow

1. Create a branch from `main`
2. Make small, focused commits
3. Open a Pull Request early (draft if WIP)
4. Ensure CI passes before requesting review
5. Request review when ready
6. Squash-merge into `main`
7. Delete the branch after merge

## Pull Request Conventions

### PR Title

Use conventional commit format:

```
feat(users): add PATCH endpoint for profile updates
fix(auth): handle expired refresh token gracefully
perf(orders): add index on orders.created_at
docs(api-design): document cursor pagination pattern
chore(deps): upgrade {{ framework }} to latest patch
```

**Scope** is the resource or module affected: `users`, `auth`, `orders`, `config`, `middleware`, etc.

### PR Description

Every PR should include:

- **What**: brief summary of the changes
- **Why**: motivation or ticket reference
- **How**: implementation approach if non-obvious
- **API changes**: list any new, modified, or removed endpoints
- **Testing**: how the change was verified (unit tests added, manual curl commands, etc.)

### Review Expectations

- Review within 1 business day
- Approve with minor comments rather than blocking on style
- Block on: correctness issues, security concerns, missing tests, undocumented API changes
- Use `[nit]` prefix for style/preference comments that do not block approval

## API Versioning

The API is versioned via the URL path: `/api/v1/...`

### Rules for Versioning

- Non-breaking changes (new optional fields, new endpoints) can be added to the current version
- Breaking changes (removing fields, changing field types, changing semantics) require a new version
- Deprecated fields are annotated in the OpenAPI spec before removal
- A version is not removed until all known consumers have migrated

### What Counts as a Breaking Change

| Change | Breaking? |
|--------|-----------|
| Add a new optional request field | No |
| Add a new response field | No (consumers must ignore unknown fields) |
| Add a new endpoint | No |
| Remove a request or response field | Yes |
| Change a field type | Yes |
| Change a field name | Yes |
| Change HTTP status code for success | Yes |
| Add a required request field | Yes |
| Change authentication requirement | Yes |

## Error Handling Conventions

All errors use a consistent JSON envelope. Never return a plain string error.

```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "ERROR_CODE",
    "message": "Human-readable description.",
    "details": []
  }
}
```

### Standard Error Codes

| HTTP Status | Code | When to Use |
|-------------|------|-------------|
| 400 | `VALIDATION_ERROR` | Request body or query params failed validation |
| 400 | `INVALID_REQUEST` | Malformed JSON, missing required fields |
{% if use_auth %}
| 401 | `UNAUTHORIZED` | Missing or invalid authentication credentials |
| 403 | `FORBIDDEN` | Authenticated but not authorized for this resource |
{% endif %}
| 404 | `NOT_FOUND` | Resource does not exist |
| 409 | `CONFLICT` | Resource already exists (e.g., duplicate email) |
| 422 | `UNPROCESSABLE` | Input is valid but violates a business rule |
| 429 | `RATE_LIMITED` | Too many requests |
| 500 | `INTERNAL_ERROR` | Unexpected server error |
| 503 | `SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE` | Dependency is down |

### Rules

- Never expose stack traces or internal error messages in responses
- Log the full error (including stack trace) server-side with a correlation ID
- Include the correlation ID in the `X-Request-ID` response header so clients can reference it in support tickets
- `VALIDATION_ERROR` must include a `details` array listing each invalid field

## Testing Expectations

Strategy: **{{ test_strategy }}**

{% if test_strategy == "unit-and-integration" %}
### Unit Tests

- Every service method has at least one unit test
- Repositories are mocked using a test double in service tests
- Test happy path, validation failures, and key edge cases
- Aim for >80% coverage on all service and utility code
- Tests run in <5 seconds total; no real database or network

### Integration Tests

- Every route is covered by at least one integration test using a real {{ database }} instance
- Test the full request-to-database cycle including auth middleware
- Integration test database is seeded and torn down per test suite
- Tests should be independent: each test sets up its own state
{% elif test_strategy == "contract-testing" %}
### Contract Tests

- Consumers define contracts that describe the API shape they depend on
- Provider verification runs against the real API on every CI build
- A failing contract test blocks the build - it means a consumer is broken
- Contracts are version-controlled alongside the API

### Integration Tests

- Repository layer: every query method tested against a real {{ database }} instance
- Service layer: tested with real repositories (no mocking at this layer)

### Unit Tests

- Complex transformation logic, validators, and utilities have unit tests
- Keep unit tests focused on code that has branching logic
{% elif test_strategy == "full-pyramid" %}
### Unit Tests (most)

- Every service method
- Every validation rule
- Every data transformation utility
- Target: >80% line coverage, 100% branch coverage on business logic

### Integration Tests (some)

- Every repository method against a real {{ database }} instance
- Every route via HTTP client against a running test application
- Auth middleware and permission checks

### Contract Tests (few)

- Top-level consumer-driven contracts for the most critical resources
- Run in CI against the real provider
{% endif %}

### Test Naming

```
test_<subject>_<scenario>_<expected_result>
```

Examples:
- `test_create_user_with_duplicate_email_returns_409`
- `test_list_orders_with_date_filter_returns_filtered_results`
- `test_delete_resource_as_non_owner_returns_403`

### Test File Location

- Unit tests: alongside source files, or in `tests/` mirroring the `src/` structure
- Integration tests: in `tests/integration/`, named after the resource (`users.integration.test.*`)

## Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)

Significant architectural decisions are documented in `docs/adrs/`.

### When to Write an ADR

- Introducing a new library or framework dependency
- Changing the database schema in a significant way
- Establishing a new API design pattern or convention
- Choosing between multiple valid implementation approaches
- Deprecating or removing an API resource
- Changing the authentication strategy

### ADR Format

```markdown
# ADR-NNNN: Title

## Status
Proposed | Accepted | Deprecated | Superseded by ADR-XXXX

## Context
What is the problem, constraint, or opportunity?

## Decision
What did we decide to do?

## Consequences
Positive and negative trade-offs. What becomes easier? What becomes harder?

## References
Links to related ADRs, docs, or external resources.
```

## Documentation Expectations

| Document | When to Update |
|----------|---------------|
| `README.md` | When setup steps or environment variables change |
| `docs/architecture.md` | When layers, responsibilities, or major components change |
| `docs/api-design.md` | When new conventions are established for REST design |
| `docs/adrs/` | When a significant architectural decision is made |
{% if use_openapi %}
| OpenAPI spec | On every endpoint addition or modification |
{% endif %}
{% if ai_context %}
| `AI_CONTEXT.md` | When architecture rules, patterns, or conventions change |
{% endif %}

## AI Collaboration Guidelines

{% if ai_context %}
This project is designed for AI-assisted development.

### For AI Agents

- Read `AI_CONTEXT.md` before starting any task
- Follow the layered architecture: routes call services, services call repositories
- Match the existing test strategy: **{{ test_strategy }}**
- Use the error codes and response envelope defined in `docs/api-design.md`
- Write an ADR when introducing a new library or significant pattern
{% if use_auth %}
- Always include authorization checks when adding endpoints that access user-owned data
{% endif %}

### For Developers Working with AI

- Provide clear, scoped task descriptions referencing specific resources or endpoints
- Reference existing files (e.g., "follow the pattern in `src/routes/users.py`")
- Review AI-generated code against the same standards as human-written code
- Update `AI_CONTEXT.md` when patterns change so future AI sessions stay aligned
{% else %}
When using AI coding assistants on this project:

- Provide the project structure and relevant conventions as context
- Reference `docs/architecture.md` and `docs/api-design.md` for existing patterns
- Review generated code for correct error handling, auth checks, and test coverage
- Ensure generated code follows the layer separation rules
{% endif %}

## Communication

- Prefer async communication: PR comments, ADRs, and doc updates over Slack threads
- Document decisions, not just outcomes
- When a significant design question arises in a PR review, elevate it to an ADR
- Keep the `docs/` folder up to date - stale documentation is worse than no documentation
